text.tspan: The initial walking corresponds to the time interval
from 0 to 3 minutes; the volunteer’s heart rate was
100 beats per minute during the frst 3 minutes. The
jogging corresponds to the increasing portion of the
graph, with the interval from 3 to 4 minutes, and an
increase in the heart rate to about 155 beats per min-
utes. From 4 to 9 minutes, the volunteer maintained
the higher speed, and the heart rate rose to about
185beats per minute. The decreasing portion, from
9to 20 minutes, corresponds to the cool down walk-
ing period; the heart rate at this decreased rapidly and
leveled off to about 100 beats per minute.
3.7348 When the input to the common logarithm is
multiplied by 10, the output is increased by 1.
1.2041 When the input to the common logarithm is
doubled, the output is increased by about 0.3010.
